{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"93d71844-683c-4cb1-a34a-9c172e093450","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic async Task MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\n> **Note:** In xUnit, `Skip` is a property on `[Fact]`/`[Theory]`, not a separate attribute. In the other three frameworks it's a standalone attribute placed alongside `[Test]`/`[TestMethod]`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bdabb876-234b-4162-8f80-b0c4aa062312","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":335,"requestId":"7035:32FCC3:F085:12495:69F2AC3F"},"id":"d9f362d3-2969-4f1a-9695-073885135868","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:11:33.945Z","parentId":"37467e34-db12-4dc2-b9fd-e03aa89e5b89"}
